{"title_page": "C. J. Laing", "text_new": "{{short description|American pornographic actress}}\n{{Infobox adult biography\n| name            = C.J. Laing\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1956|08|1|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| spouse          = \n| height          = \n| weight          = \n| alias           = Jessie Savage, C.J. Lang, Chris Jackson, Gwen Starr, Gwen Fisher, Jessy Lang\n| nocat_wdimage   = yes\n| website         = \n}}\n'''C.J. Laing''' (born August 1, 1956) is an American former [[adult entertainment]] performer, appearing in films during the 1970s. She is a member of the [[AVN Hall of Fame]] and the [[XRCO Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avnawards.com/halloffame.php|title=AVN Hall of Fame|access-date=August 16, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814014605/http://www.avnawards.com/halloffame.php|archive-date=August 14, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=XRCO>{{cite web|url=http://www.dirtybob.com/xrco/hall.htm|title=XRCO Hall of Fame|access-date=January 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Adult film career==\nC.J. Laing, a native of [[New York City|New York]], was living in [[San Francisco]].{{sfn|McNeil|Osborne|Pavia|2005|p=82\u201383}} A fan of 1970s San Francisco music, she hitchhiked there and stayed in a communal house with the Angels of Light. To earn extra money, she auditioned for the [[Mitchell Brothers]] and appeared in a \"loop\" as part of the series \"Juke Joint.\"{{sfn|McNeil|Osborne|Pavia|2005|p=82\u201383}}<ref name=Maniacs>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdmaniacs.net/forums/archive/index.php?t-13699.html|title=The C. J. Laing Thread|publisher=The DVD Maniacs|access-date=October 12, 2007}}</ref> In New York, the Mitchell Brothers introduced her to the Buckley Brothers who cast her in her first feature film with [[Jamie Gillis]] in 1974 under the name Gwen Starr.<ref name=Maniacs />{{sfn|McNeil|Osborne|Pavia|2005|p=145}}\n\nLaing appeared in over 50 films and \"loops\" during the 1970s and is best known for her roles in ''Anyone But My Husband'' and ''[[Barbara Broadcast]]''.<ref name=\"NYT-1977\">{{cite news|title=Barbara Broadcast (1977)|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/430120/Barbara-Broadcast/details|date=1977|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=February 19, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"PC-20131021\">{{cite web|last=Drain|first=Heather|title=Radley Metzger's Barbara Broadcast - Notes From The Backroom|url=http://paracinema.net/2013/10/radley-metzgers-barbara-broadcast/|date=October 21, 2016|work=Paracinema.com|access-date=February 21, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"MD-20130827\">{{cite web|title=Barbara Broadcast - BluRay DVD Review|url=http://www.mondo-digital.com/barbarabroadcast.html|date=August 27, 2013|work=Mondo-digital.com|access-date=February 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nLaing is quoted in ''[[Time Magazine]]'' as saying: \"I purposely would not act, I despised the people in these films that said they were actors. I was like, 'You've got to be kidding me! This is about fucking and sucking!{{'}}\"<ref name=Time>{{cite news|last=Corliss|first=Richard|title=That Old Feeling: When Porno Was Chic|author-link=Richard Corliss|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|url=http://www.time.com/time/columnist/corliss/article/0,9565,1043267-2,00.html|date=March 29, 2005|access-date=September 25, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071002215837/http://www.time.com/time/columnist/corliss/article/0,9565,1043267-2,00.html|archive-date=October 2, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDuring the late 1970s, Laing performed live shows at the [[Mitchell Brothers O'Farrell Theatre]] and other theaters owned by the Mitchell Brothers.<ref name=Maniacs /> Her last film was ''New York City Woman'' in 1979.<ref name=IAFD>{{Iafd name|CJLaing|f|C.J. Laing}}. Retrieved April 16, 2017.</ref>\n\nLaing was inducted into the [[X-Rated Critics Organization]] [[XRCO Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] as a \"Film Pioneer\" in 1989.<ref name=XRCO/><ref>Jeremy Stone, \"Heart-ons in Hollywood: The 5th Annual XRCO Adult Film & Video Awards\", ''Adam Film World'', September 1989, Vol. 13, No. 1, p. 10\u201311, 54.</ref><ref name=\"afwg1990dir\">\"The XRCO Hall of Fame\", ''Adam Film World Guide 1990 Directory of Adult Films'', p. 17.</ref> In 2005, she was also inducted into the [[AVN Hall of Fame]] as \"one of the most exciting stars of the so-called [[Golden Age of Porn|Golden Age of porn]]\" and as \"an energetic performer who turned in some of the strongest performances of her time.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Andersson|first=Acme|title=The 2005 AVN Hall of Fame Inductees|work=[[Adult Video News]]|url=http://www.adultvideonews.com/hall/hall0305_01.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050318015401/http://www.adultvideonews.com/hall/hall0305_01.html|archive-date=March 18, 2005|access-date=October 12, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n* ''Oriental Blue'' (1975)\n* ''Anyone But My Husband'' (1975)\n* ''[[The Vixens of Kung Fu]]'' (1975)\n* ''Sweet Punkin'' (1976)\n* ''[[Water Power (film)|Water Power]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Barbara Broadcast]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[Unwilling Lovers]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[Maraschino Cherry (1978 film)|Maraschino Cherry]]'' (1978)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|last1=McNeil|first1=Legs|author1-link=Legs McNeil|last2=Osborne|first2=Jennifer|last3=Pavia|first3=Peter|title=The Other Hollywood: The Uncensored Oral History of the Porn Film Industry|year=2005|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|isbn=0-06-009659-4|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|C.J. Laing}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=0481896|name=C.J. Laing}}\n* {{iafd name|id=CJLaing|gender=female|name=C.J. Laing}}\n* {{afdb name|id=1590|gender=female|name=C.J. Laing}}\n{{Radley Metzger}}\n{{Sexual revolution}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Society|Film|United States}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTS