i dead: Former Chelsea and England goalkeeper 'The Cat' passes away, aged 78|work=Evening Standard|date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Tim Brooke-Taylor]], 79, comedian ([[The Goodies]]) and panelist (''[[I'm Sorry I Haven't a Clue]]''), [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Cockroft|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/tim-brooketaylor-dead-dies-79-coronavirus-a4412831.html|title=Tim Brooke-Taylor dead: Comedian and actor dies aged 79 after contracting coronavirus|work=Evening Standard|date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Sir Stirling Moss]], 90, [[International Motorsports Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] [[Formula One]] driver.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Stirling Moss: Motor racing legend dies aged 90 after long illness|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/52261216|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n*13 April\n**[[Peter Madden (footballer)|Peter Madden]], 85, English footballer ([[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]]) and football manager ([[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]], [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]]).<ref>{{cite news|last=Atkinson|first=Nathan|url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/18380678.bradford-born-star-played-first-league-cup-final-dies/|title=Bradford born star who played in first League Cup final dies|work=Telegraph and Argus|date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Avrohom Pinter]], 71, rabbi and politician, [[Hackney London Borough Council|Hackney Borough councillor]] (1982\u20131990), [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/article/H1SjjSzOI|title=Renowned British Rabbi Avraham Pinter succumbs to COVID-19|publisher=Ynet News|date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n*14 April\n**[[Pip Baker]], 91, screenwriter (''[[Doctor Who]]'').<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2020/04/pip-baker-died-2020.html|title=Pip Baker 1928 \u2013 2020|publisher=Doctor Who News|date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[John Collins (footballer, born 1949)|John Collins]], 71, Welsh footballer ([[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], [[Halifax Town F.C.|Halifax Town]], [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2020/april/obituary-john-collins/|title=Obituary \u2013 John Collins|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Cyril Lawrence]], 99, English footballer ([[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]], [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]]), [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salfordstar.com/article.asp?id=5555|title=99 year old Salford man and ex-pro footballer beaten by coronavirus|work=Salford Star|date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[John Lee (Labour politician)|John Lee]], 92, politician, MP (1966\u20131970, 1974\u20131979).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/article/remembrance-of-departed-colleagues|title=Members of our Association who have died during 2020|work=Politics Home|date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Sir Hugh Rossi]], 92, politician, [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] (1966\u20131992) and [[Minister for Disabled People|Minister for Social Security]] (1981\u20131983).<ref>{{cite news|last=Boniface|first=Michael|url=https://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/sir-hugh-rossi-hornsey-mp-haringey-councillor-dies-1-6606918|title=Sir Hugh Rossi: Former Hornsey MP and councillor dies aged 92|work=Ham and High|date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n*15 April\n**[[Joe Brown (climber)|Joe Brown]], 89, mountaineer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brown|first=Nick|url=https://www.ukclimbing.com/news/2020/04/climbing_pioneer_joe_brown_dies_aged_89-72275|title=Climbing Pioneer Joe Brown dies aged 89|publisher=UK Climbing|date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[John T. Houghton|Sir John Houghton]], 88, atmospheric physicist, [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2020/17-april/features/interviews/from-the-archives-interview-sir-john-houghton-meteorologist-climate-change-expert|title=From the archives: Interview: Sir John Houghton, meteorologist, climate-change expert|work=Church Times|date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Bruce Myers (actor)|Bruce Myers]], 77\u201378, actor (''[[The Unbearable Lightness of Being (film)|The Unbearable Lightness of Being]]'', ''[[Let There Be Light (1998 film)|Let There Be Light]]''), comedian, and director.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sceneweb.fr/la-mort-du-comedien-bruce-myers/|title=La mort du com\u00e9dien Bruce Myers|date=16 April 2020|publisher=Sceneweb.Fr|language=fr}}</ref>\n*17 April\n**[[Norman Hunter (footballer)|Norman Hunter]], 76, English footballer ([[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]], [[England national football team|national team]]) and football manager, world champion ([[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966]]), [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Paul|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/apr/17/norman-hunter-former-leeds-united-england-defender-dies-aged-76|title=Norman Hunter, former Leeds and England defender, dies aged 76|work=The Guardian|date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Matthew Seligman]], 64, new wave bassist ([[The Soft Boys]], [[Thompson Twins]]), [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Bloom|first=Madison|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-soft-boys-matthew-seligman-has-died/|title=The Soft Boys\u2019 Matthew Seligman Has Died|publisher=Pitchfork.com|date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n*19 April\n**[[Terry Doran]], 83\u201384, music manager ([[Grapefruit (band)|Grapefruit]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bestclassicbands.com/terry-doran-beatles-dead-4-19-20/|title=Beatles Associate Terry Doran Dies: Report|publisher=Best Classic Bands|date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Dickie Dowsett]], 88, English footballer ([[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]], [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]], [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.afcb.co.uk/news/club-news/club-mourns-dickie-dowsett/|title=Club Mourns Dickie Dowsett|publisher=A.F.C. Bournemouth|date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Ian Whitcomb]], 78, singer-songwriter (\"[[You Turn Me On (song)|You Turn Me On]]\") and author.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tamarkin|first=Jeff|url=https://bestclassicbands.com/ian-whitcomb-you-turn-me-on-obituary-4-20-20/|title=Ian Whitcomb \u2018You Turn Me On\u2019 Singer, Dead at 78|publisher=Best Classic Bands|date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n*20 April \u2013 [[Manjeet Singh Riyat]], 52, head of emergency care at the [[Royal Derby Hospital]], [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref name=\"Walker\">{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Amy |title=UK's first Sikh A&E consultant dies at his hospital after Covid-19 diagnosis |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/21/uks-first-sikh-ae-consultant-dies-at-his-hospital-after-covid-19-diagnosis |accessdate=21 April 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 April 2020 |quote=he became the first Sikh to be appointed as an emergency medicine consultant in the UK.}}</ref>\n*21 April\n**[[Ingrid Allen|Dame Ingrid Allen]], 87, neuropathologist.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hewitt|first=Ralph|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/dame-ingrid-victoria-allen-qub-neuroscience-professor-had-amazing-talent-and-endless-energy-39152781.html|title=Dame Ingrid Victoria Allen: QUB neuroscience professor 'had amazing talent and endless energy'|work=Belfast Telegraph|date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Dave Bacuzzi]], 79, English footballer ([[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], [[Reading F.C.|Reading]]) and football manager, [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Malone|first=Emmet|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/national-league/former-cork-hibs-and-home-farm-boss-david-bacuzzi-dies-from-covid-19-1.4235226|title=Former Cork Hibs and Home Farm boss David Bacuzzi dies from Covid-19|work=Irish Times|date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n*22 April\n**[[Eric Anderson (teacher)|Sir Eric Anderson]], 83, educator, [[List of Head Masters of Eton College|Headmaster]] (1980\u20131994) and [[Provost of Eton|Provost]] (2000\u20132009) of [[Eton College]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://internewscast.com/former-eton-headmaster-eric-anderson-dies-aged-83/|title=Former Eton headmaster Eric Anderson dies aged 83|publisher=Internewscast|date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Terence Frisby]], 87, playwright (''[[There's a Girl in My Soup (play)|There's a Girl in My Soup]]'') and actor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/obituaries/2020/04/23/terence-frisby-actor-playwright-made-name-girl-soup-obituary/|title=Terence Frisby, actor and playwright who made his name with \u2018There\u2019s a Girl in My Soup\u2019 \u2013 obituary|work=Daily Telegraph|date=23 April 2020}} {{paywall}}</ref>\n**[[Jimmy Goodfellow]], 76, English footballer ([[Workington A.F.C.|Workington]], [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]]) and football manager ([[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/52384399|title=Jimmy Goodfellow: Former Cardiff City manager dies aged 76|work=BBC Sport|date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Peter Jonas (director)|Sir Peter Jonas]], 73, arts administrator and opera director.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.spiegel.de/kultur/musik/peter-jonas-ist-tot-a-7cbe400b-ef00-4bd6-a54f-5d536a4df4d6|title=Sir Peter Jonas ist tot|work=Der Spiegel|date=23 April 2020|language=de}}</ref>\n*23 April \u2013 [[Patrick Leo McCartie]], 94, Roman Catholic prelate, Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Northampton|Northampton]] (1990\u20132001).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bmccartie.html|title=Bishop Patrick Leo McCartie|publisher=Catholic Hierarchy|date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n*24 April \u2013 [[Lynn Faulds Wood]], 72, television presenter (''[[Watchdog (TV programme)|Watchdog]]'') and journalist.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52410491|title=Former Watchdog host Lynn Faulds Wood dies aged 72|work=BBC News|date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n*25 April \u2013 [[Liz Edgar]], 76, showjumper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishshowjumping.co.uk/news/liz-edgar-28-april-1943--25-april-2020|title=Liz Edgar (28 April 1943 \u2013 25 April 2020)|date=2020-04-25|access-date=2020-04-28|website=British Showjumping}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Politics of the United Kingdom]]\n*[[2020s in United Kingdom political history]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}{{Years in the United Kingdom}}\n[[Category:2020 in the United Kingdom| ]]\n[[Category:2010s in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2020 by country|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2020 in Europe|United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date = November 2018}}\n{{Year in United Kingdom|2020|label1=Individual countries of the United Kingdom|data1=[[2020 in England|England]] {{!}} [[2020 in Northern Ireland|Northern Ireland]] {{!}} [[2020 in Scotland|Scotland]] {{!}} [[2020 in Wales|Wales]]|label2=Popular culture |data2=<div>\n[[Football in the United Kingdom|Football]]: [[2019\u201320 in English football|England]] {{!}} [[2019\u201320 in Scottish football|Scotland]] {{!}} [[2019\u201320 in Welsh football|Wales]]<br />\n[[2020 British Grand Prix]]<br />\n[[2020 English cricket season]]<br />\n[[2020 in British television]]<br />\n[[2020 in British music]]<br />\n[[2020 in British radio]]<br />\n[[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020|UK in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020]]\n</div>}}\nEvents from the year '''2020 in the United Kingdom'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[Monarch of the United Kingdom|Monarch]] \u2013 [[Elizabeth II]]\n*[[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] \u2013 [[Boris Johnson]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]])\n*[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] \u2013 [[List of MPs elected in the 2019 United Kingdom general election|58th]]\n\n== Events ==\n\n=== January ===\n*4 January \u2013 The [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] warns British nationals against all but essential travel to [[Iran]] and [[Iraq]], following [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|a US airstrike in Baghdad]] the previous day in which Iranian general [[Qasem Soleimani]] was killed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50991778 |title=Qasem Soleimani: Foreign Office hardens Iran and Iraq travel advice |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=4 January 2020 |accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n*5 January \u2013 Boris Johnson says \"we will not lament\" Qasem Soleimani's death as he calls for \"de-escalation from all sides\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51001236 |title=Qasem Soleimani: PM 'will not lament' Iranian general's death |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 January 2020 |accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n*6 January\n**[[Reynhard Sinaga]], described as \"the most prolific rapist in British legal history\", is sentenced to life in prison with a minimum term of 30 years, after being found guilty of raping or sexually assaulting 48 men in Manchester. Police believe he may have been responsible for assaulting a total of nearly 200 victims.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/jan/06/reynhard-sinaga-jailed-life-drugging-raping-men-manchester |title=Reynhard Sinaga: man jailed for life for raping dozens of men in Manchester |work=The Guardian|date=6 January 2020 |accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Downing Street]] states that Britain will not support U.S. President [[Donald Trump]]'s threat to bomb Iranian cultural and heritage sites.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/06/no-10-uk-would-not-back-us-bombing-of-iranian-cultural-sites|title=UK would not back US bombing of Iran cultural sites \u2013 No 10|work=The Guardian|date=6 January 2020 |accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n*7 January \u2013 The [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|Labour Party leadership election]] formally begins, with the new leader scheduled to be announced on 4 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51000133 |title=Labour leadership: Result will be announced on 4 April |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 January 2020 |accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n*8 January \u2013 [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex]], and [[Meghan, Duchess of Sussex]], announce that they plan to \"step back as senior members\" of [[British Royal family|Britain's royal family]], and divide their time between the UK and North America.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51040751 |title=Harry and Meghan to step back as senior royals |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=8 January 2020 |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n*9 January \n**The [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] gives its third and final backing to the [[European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Bill 2019\u201320|Withdrawal Agreement Bill]], voting 330 to 231 in favour; the bill now passes to the [[House of Lords (United Kingdom)|House of Lords]] for scrutiny.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51051178 |title=MPs give final backing to Brexit bill |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=9 January 2020 |accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n**The UK and Irish governments publish [[2020 Northern Ireland Agreement|a deal]] aimed at restoring the [[Northern Ireland Executive]]; the [[Democratic Unionist Party]] gives its backing to the agreement.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Andrew |last=Madden |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/dup-accept-governments-draft-agreement-to-restore-stormont-sinn-fein-studying-text-38849112.html |title=DUP accept governments' draft agreement to restore Stormont, Sinn Fein 'studying' text |work=Belfast Telegraph |publisher=Independent News and Media |date=9 January 2020 |accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n*10 January \u2013 [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] gives its backing to [[2020 Northern Ireland Agreement|a deal]] to restore power-sharing government to Northern Ireland for the first time since 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-51068774 |title=Sinn F\u00e9in agrees to rejoin NI government after deal |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=10 January 2020 |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n*11 January  \n**The [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] reconvenes after a three-year hiatus; [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]] leader [[Arlene Foster]] is appointed [[First Minister of Northern Ireland|Northern Ireland's first minister]], while [[Sinn Fein]]'s [[Michelle O'Neill]] is appointed [[Deputy First Minister of Northern Ireland|deputy first minister]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-51077397 |title=Stormont deal: Arlene Foster and Michelle O'Neill new top NI ministers |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 January 2020 |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Robert Macaire (diplomat)|Robert Macaire]], the British ambassador to [[Iran]], is briefly detained in Iran after attending a vigil for those killed on [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]]. Iran summoned him to appear at [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Iran)|its foreign ministry]] the following day after saying he had been \"an unknown foreigner in an illegal gathering\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51077897 |title=Iran plane crash: Britain condemns Tehran's arrest of UK ambassador |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 January 2020 |accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n*13 January \u2013 Following a meeting of senior royals, [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] agrees to a \"period of transition\" during which the Duke and Duchess of Sussex will spend time in Canada and the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51099102 |title=Queen agrees 'transition' to new role for Harry and Meghan |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 January 2020 |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n*14 January\n**The government agrees a rescue package for troubled regional airline [[Flybe]] to stop it going into administration.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51113895 |title=Flybe: Government strikes a deal to rescue troubled airline |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 January 2020 |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n**Boris Johnson formally rejects [[First Minister of Scotland|Scottish First Minister]] [[Nicola Sturgeon]]'s request for a [[Proposed second Scottish independence referendum|second independence referendum]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-51106796 |title=Scottish independence: Johnson rejects Sturgeon's indyref2 demand |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 January 2020 |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n*16 January \u2013 Legislation is drafted before Parliament allowing the use of [[Professional video camera|television cameras]] during trials at [[Crown Court]]s in England and Wales, but only the [[judge]]s will be filmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51110206 |title=TV cameras to be allowed in Crown Courts in England and Wales |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 January 2020 |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n*17 January \u2013 Construction begins on [[Dogger Bank Wind Farm]], which will become the world's largest offshore wind farm when complete, with 260-metre high turbines generating a combined 3.6 gigawatts and supplying 4.5 million homes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/amp/2020/01/17/work-starts-on-huge-wind-farm-that-could-power-4point5-million-homes.html |title=Work starts on world's 'largest offshore wind farm' that could power 4.5 million homes|publisher=CNBC|date=17 January 2020 |accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n*18 January \u2013 [[Buckingham Palace]] confirms that from spring 2020 the Duke and Duchess of Sussex will no longer use their royal titles and will no longer receive public funds for their royal duties.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51163865 |title=Harry and Meghan lose funding and drop HRH titles |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=18 January 2020 |accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n*21 January \u2013 The [[Office of Rail and Road]] announces that [[Network Rail]] is being investigated over its poor performance on routes used by train operators [[Arriva Rail North]] and [[TransPennine Express]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/network-rail-being-investigated-for-poor-performance-11914036 |title=Network Rail being investigated for 'poor performance' |publisher=Sky News|date=21 January 2020 |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n*22 January \u2013 Boris Johnson's EU withdrawal deal successfully completes its passage through parliament, with the [[European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Act 2020|EU Withdrawal Agreement Bill]] being voted through without change, after several amendments proposed by the House of Lords are rejected.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51214761 |title=Brexit: UK has 'crossed Brexit finish line', says Boris Johnson |date=22 January 2020 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n*23 January\n**Parliamentary ratification of Boris Johnson's EU withdrawal deal is completed with [[Royal Assent]] being given to the [[European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Act 2020|EU Withdrawal Agreement Bill]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20200123IPR70904/brexit-the-withdrawal-agreement-passes-the-first-european-parliament-test |title=Brexit: the Withdrawal Agreement passes the first European Parliament test |date=23 January 2020 |work=News |publisher=European Parliament}}</ref>\n**An [[2002 Dudley earthquake|earthquake]] of 3.0 magnitude is recorded by the [[British Geological Survey]] in [[Stockton-on-Tees]], [[County Durham]], just before 6am.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/jan/23/teesside-shaken-by-earthquake-stockton-durham |title=Teesside shaken by 3.0-magnitude earthquake |work=The Guardian|date=23 January 2020 |accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n*24 January\n**The UK's EU withdrawal agreement is signed by both parties; firstly in the morning in [[Brussels]], by [[European Council]] president [[Charles Michel]] and [[European Commission]] president [[Ursula von der Leyen]] for the EU, then after travelling on the [[Eurostar]] in a diplomatic case, in [[London]] in the afternoon by Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] for the UK.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51244126 |title=Brexit: Boris Johnson signs withdrawal agreement in Downing Street |date=24 January 2020 |work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/24/sombre-eu-leaders-sign-brexit-withdrawal-agreement |title='Fantastic moment': Boris Johnson signs Brexit withdrawal deal |date=24 January 2020 |last1=Proctor |first1=Kate |last2=Boffey |first2=Daniel |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n**Police announce that live [[Facial recognition system|facial recognition technology]] will be rolled out across London.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-security-cameras/police-to-roll-out-live-facial-recognition-cameras-in-london-idUKKBN1ZN1H5 |title=Police to roll out live facial recognition cameras in London |publisher=Reuters|date=24 January 2020 |accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n*25 January \u2013 A newly-appointed member of the [[Grenfell Tower Inquiry|Grenfell Tower fire public enquiry panel]] resigns after being linked to the company which supplied cladding for the block.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51252297 |title=Grenfell Tower inquiry member Benita Mehra resigns |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=25 January 2020 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n*27 January \u2013 The Health Secretary, [[Matt Hancock]], tells the House of Commons that 200 British citizens trapped in [[Wuhan]], [[China]], will be offered repatriation to the UK, in light of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak in Hubei|coronavirus outbreak there]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/27/britons-in-wuhan-will-be-offered-help-to-leave-hancock-tells-mps |title=Britons in Wuhan will be offered help to leave, Hancock tells MPs |work=The Guardian|date=27 January 2020 |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n*28 January \u2013 The Prime Minister approves a limited \"non-core\" role for China's [[Huawei]] in Britain's [[5G]] mobile network, resisting U.S. pressure to exclude the company on fears China could use it to steal data.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/jan/28/boris-johnson-gives-green-light-for-huawei-5g-infrastructure-role |title=Boris Johnson gives green light for Huawei 5G infrastructure role |work=The Guardian|date=28 January 2020 |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n*29 January\n**[[British Airways]] suspends all flights to and from mainland China with immediate effect, due to the ongoing coronavirus threat.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/29/evacuation-of-britons-in-coronavirus-hit-hubei-could-begin-thursday |title=Britons evacuated due to coronavirus to be quarantined |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper==The Guardian |date=29 January 2020 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n**Transport Secretary [[Grant Shapps]] announces that troubled train operator [[Arriva Rail North]] will be brought under government control from 1 March following a prolonged period of delays and poor performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-51298820 |title=Troubled rail firm Northern brought under government control |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=29 January 2020 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n**''[[The Guardian]]'' announces that it will no longer accept advertising from oil and gas companies, becoming the first major global news organisation to institute an outright ban on taking money from the fossil fuel industry.<ref>{{cite news|u