e UK]]: The 50th anniversary [[Glastonbury Festival]] is cancelled as a result of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/18/uk-coronavirus-live-boris-johnson-pmqs-cbi-urges-government-pay-businesses-directly-saying-350bn-loangrant-package-not-enough |title=All schools to close from Friday; GCSE and A-level exams cancelled \u2013 UK coronavirus, as it happened |work=The Guardian |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The government announces emergency legislation to bring in a complete ban on new evictions for three months as part of measures to help protect renters in social and private rented accommodation.\n*19 March \u2013 In an emergency move, the Bank of England cuts interest rates again, from 0.25% to just 0.1%. This is the lowest ever in the Bank's 325-year history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51962982 |title=Coronavirus: UK interest rates slashed to lowest level ever |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*20 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Northwick Park Hospital]] in [[London Borough of Harrow|Harrow]] declares a \"critical incident\" due to a surge in patients with coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/news/hospitals-critical-care-unit-overwhelmed-by-coronavirus-patients/7027189.article |title=Hospital's critical care unit overwhelmed by coronavirus patients |work=HSJ |publisher=HSJ|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Chancellor Rishi Sunak announces that the government will pay 80% of wages for employees not working, up to \u00a32,500 a month, as part of \"unprecedented\" measures to protect people's jobs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51982005 |title=Wages cover for businesses hit by virus outlined |publisher=BBC News|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister Boris Johnson orders all cafes, pubs and restaurants to close from the evening of 20 March, except for take-away food, to tackle coronavirus. All the UK's nightclubs, theatres, cinemas, gyms and leisure centres are told to close \"as soon as they reasonably can\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51981653 |title=UK pubs and restaurants told to shut in virus fight |publisher=BBC News|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n*21 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]] [[George Eustice]] urges shoppers to stop [[panic buying]], as supermarkets around the UK struggle to keep up with demand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51989721 |title=Coronavirus: Shoppers told to buy responsibly |publisher=BBC News|date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> [[Tesco]], [[Asda]], [[Aldi]], and [[Lidl]] are reported to have begun a recruitment drive for up to 30,000 new staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51976075 |title=Supermarkets Tesco, Asda, Aldi and Lidl go on hiring spree |publisher=BBC News|date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n*22 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The [[Nursing and Midwifery Council]] announces that more than 5,600 former nurses have registered to offer their services in the fight against coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/22/uk-coronavirus-live-police-could-enforce-london-lockdown-says-khan-seven-people-die-in-wales?page=with:block-5e776a4f8f08dcc95cc20fdd#block-5e776a4f8f08dcc95cc20fdd |title=UK coronavirus live: police could enforce London social distancing; seven people die in Wales |work=The Guardian|date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Boris Johnson warns that \"tougher measures\" may be introduced if people do not follow government advice on social distancing.<ref name=\"tougher measures\">{{cite news|url